    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>KLM SHARES SINK</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Suzanne Kapner</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Kapner, Suzanne</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Shares of KLM, Dutch airline, sink 21 percent following collapse of merger discussions with British Airways (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>In a show of uncertainty over the future of KLM, the Dutch airline, its shares tumbled 21 percent, to 21.5 euros, or $18.89, their biggest one-day decline ever, after the collapse of merger talks with British Airways. The British airline's shares fell less than 1 percent, to 295.25 pence, or $4.14, after having risen as much as 5.8 percent in intraday trading. Most analysts agree that KLM is too small to survive on its own, but the list of possible partners is dwindling. Earlier this year, KLM abandoned merger talks with Alitalia of Italy.</p>
        <p>Suzanne Kapner</p>
      </block>
